{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3640256,"name":"gartaud","username":"gartaud","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/g/a4c791/{size}.png","created_at":"2025-05-30T00:13:28.466Z","cooked":"<p>Hello</p>
<p>I am looking for an example of a WPILib SwerveControllerCommand following a trajectory with a <span class="abbreviation">CTRE<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Cross The Road Electronics"></template></span> Swerve Project-generated CommandSwerveDrivetrain</p>
<p>It’s admittedly not a super useful use-case, but it is super easy to implement with code following the MAXSwerve template and less so with the <span class="abbreviation">CTRE<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Cross The Road Electronics"></template></span> template, and is quite nice to have to debug issues without introducing a third-party planning library in the mix…</p>
<p>Thanks!</p>","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"posts_count":7,"updated_at":"2025-05-30T00:13:28.466Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":13,"reads":107,"readers_count":106,"score":86.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":502566,"topic_slug":"example-of-wpilib-swervecontrollercommand-following-trajectory-with-ctre-generated-commandswervedrivetrain","display_username":"gartaud","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":31686,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Software Engineering Mentor, 1089 & 2495"},"post_url":"/t/example-of-wpilib-swervecontrollercommand-following-trajectory-with-ctre-generated-commandswervedrivetrain/502566/1","custom_user_title":"Software Engineering Mentor, 1089 & 2495","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":true,"can_vote":false},{"id":3640295,"name":"Benjamin Hall","username":"bhall-ctre","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/bhall-ctre/{size}/198180_2.png","created_at":"2025-05-30T00:55:39.166Z","cooked":"<p>We generally advise against using <code>SwerveControllerCommand</code>, as it is not well-maintained; it doesn’t discretize the applied ChassisSpeeds, for example. The <code>SwerveControllerCommand</code> outputting module states instead of a ChassisSpeeds can also impact performance; most of our swerve requests instead offload that to the C++ layer to avoid GC overhead.</p>
<p>Instead, the command can be easily reimplemented as a factory method in your CommandSwerveDrivetrain:</p>
<pre data-code-wrap="java"><code class="lang-java">    private final HolonomicDriveController m_holonomicController = new HolonomicDriveController(
        new PIDController(...),
        new PIDController(...),
        new ProfiledPIDController(...)
    );
    private final ApplyRobotSpeeds m_pathApplyRobotSpeeds = new ApplyRobotSpeeds()
        .withDriveRequestType(DriveRequestType.OpenLoopVoltage);

    public Command runTrajectory(Trajectory trajectory) {
        final Timer timer = new Timer();
        return runOnce(timer::restart).andThen(
            applyRequest(() -&gt; {
                double curTime = timer.get();
                var desiredState = trajectory.sample(curTime);
                var targetRobotSpeeds = m_holonomicController.calculate(
                    getState().Pose, desiredState,
                    desiredState.poseMeters.getRotation()
                );
                targetRobotSpeeds = ChassisSpeeds.discretize(targetRobotSpeeds, 0.020);
                return m_pathApplyRobotSpeeds.withSpeeds(targetRobotSpeeds);
            })
            .until(() -&gt; timer.hasElapsed(trajectory.getTotalTimeSeconds()))
        );
    }
</code></pre>
<p>This also makes it easy to make improvements to the command. For example, you can swap out the <code>HolonomicDriveController</code> with an implementation that returns the field-centric <code>ChassisSpeeds</code> (without converting them to robot-centric speeds) and use our <code>ApplyFieldSpeeds</code> request, which can do the field-centric conversion at 250 Hz and automatically handles the discretization:</p>
<pre data-code-wrap="java"><code class="lang-java">    private final PIDController m_holonomicXController = new PIDController(...);
    private final PIDController m_holonomicYController = new PIDController(...);
    private final ProfiledPIDController m_holonomicThetaController = new ProfiledPIDController(...);

    private final ApplyFieldSpeeds m_pathApplyFieldSpeeds = new ApplyFieldSpeeds()
        .withDriveRequestType(DriveRequestType.OpenLoopVoltage);

    public Command runTrajectory(Trajectory trajectory) {
        m_holonomicThetaController.enableContinuousInput(-Math.PI, Math.PI);

        final Timer timer = new Timer();
        return runOnce(() -&gt; {
            m_holonomicThetaController.reset(getState().Pose.getRotation().getRadians());
            timer.restart();
        }).andThen(
            applyRequest(() -&gt; {
                double curTime = timer.get();
                var desiredState = trajectory.sample(curTime);
                var currentPose = getState().Pose;

                // Calculate feedforward velocities (field-relative).
                double xFF = desiredState.velocityMetersPerSecond * desiredState.poseMeters.getRotation().getCos();
                double yFF = desiredState.velocityMetersPerSecond * desiredState.poseMeters.getRotation().getSin();
                double thetaFF = m_holonomicThetaController.calculate(
                    currentPose.getRotation().getRadians(),
                    desiredState.poseMeters.getRotation().getRadians()
                );
                thetaFF += m_holonomicThetaController.getSetpoint().velocity;

                // Calculate feedback velocities (based on position error).
                double xFeedback = m_holonomicXController.calculate(currentPose.getX(), desiredState.poseMeters.getX());
                double yFeedback = m_holonomicYController.calculate(currentPose.getY(), desiredState.poseMeters.getY());

                var targetFieldSpeeds = new ChassisSpeeds(
                    xFF + xFeedback, yFF + yFeedback, thetaFF
                );
                return m_pathApplyFieldSpeeds.withSpeeds(targetFieldSpeeds);
            })
            .until(() -&gt; timer.hasElapsed(trajectory.getTotalTimeSeconds()))
        );
    }
</code></pre>","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"posts_count":7,"updated_at":"2025-05-30T02:20:56.757Z","reply_count":3,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":6,"reads":93,"readers_count":92,"score":123.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":502566,"topic_slug":"example-of-wpilib-swervecontrollercommand-following-trajectory-with-ctre-generated-commandswervedrivetrain","display_username":"Benjamin Hall","primary_group_name":"CTRE","flair_name":"CTRE","flair_url":"/uploads/default/original/3X/1/b/1bd2b430e1bb6427d1c6504ff6abcd31de851a6d.png","flair_bg_color":"","flair_color":"","flair_group_id":57,"badges_granted":[],"version":3,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":4}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":48146,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Software Engineering Intern at CTR Electronics"},"post_url":"/t/example-of-wpilib-swervecontrollercommand-following-trajectory-with-ctre-generated-commandswervedrivetrain/502566/2","custom_user_title":"Software Engineering Intern at CTR Electronics","reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":4}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":4,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":true,"topic_accepted_answer":true},{"id":3640299,"name":"Amicus1","username":"Amicus1","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/a/a9adbd/{size}.png","created_at":"2025-05-30T01:02:27.563Z","cooked":"<p>Also the WPILib Trajectory class is meant for differential drive, and the accompanying TrajectoryGenerator doesn’t let the robot heading be separate from the velocity vector.</p>
